{{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|12=draft}} 2 ({{ill|1869|ja|1869th year|12=draft}}) saw the enshrinement of the {{ill|Bunrei|ja|分霊|12=draft}} from the head office – {{ill|Head Office|ja|本社|lt=General Head Office|lt_ja=総本社|12=draft}} – of {{ill|Suitengu (Kurume City)|ja|水天宮 (久留米市)|lt=Kurume Suitengu|lt_ja=久留米水天宮|12=draft}}, which was combined ({{ill|合祀|1=co-Enshrinement|2=ja|3=合祀|12=draft}}) with the Inari Shrine ({{ill|Inari Shrine|ja|稲荷神社|12=draft}}) and Yaken Shrine (弥剣神社（{{ill|Gion Shrine|ja|祇園社|12=draft}}）) within the area to establish the shrine. In addition, the Inari Shrine was founded in {{ill|Bunroku|ja|文禄|12=draft}} 3 ({{ill|1587|ja|1587th year|12=draft}}) by {{ill|Tachibana Muneshige|ja|立花宗茂|12=draft}}, while the Yaken Shrine was established during the {{ill|Bunka|ja|文化 (元号)|lt=Bunka|lt_ja=文化|12=draft}} period (1804–1818).

Locally, it is known as "'''Suitengu-san'''". During the Okinohata Suitengu Festival held on May 3, 4, and 5, a boat stage called Sangu-maru is constructed and the Suitengu festival music is performed from dusk.

== 祭事 ==
[[File:Fukuoka Yanagawa10s3.jpg|thumb|水天宮大祭]]
* 2月初午日 初午祭
* 5月3～5日 水天宮大祭
* 7月20・21日 祇園祭

== Access ==
* {{ill|Nishinippon Railroad|ja|西日本鉄道|lt=Nishitetsu|lt_ja=西鉄|12=draft}}{{ill|Nishitetsu Tenjin Ōmuta Line|ja|西鉄天神大牟田線|lt=Tenjin Ōmuta Line|lt_ja=天神大牟田線|12=draft}}{{ill|Nishitetsu Yanagawa Station|ja|西鉄柳川駅|lt=Yanagawa Station|lt_ja=柳川駅|12=draft}} – alight and then:
** Board the {{ill|Nishitetsu Bus|ja|西鉄バス|12=draft}} bound for "Hayatsue" ("早津江"), alight at the "Suitengu Entrance" ("水天宮入口") bus stop; a 4‑minute walk.
** Alternatively, take the same bus bound for "Hayatsue" or the "Yanagawa Hospital Loop" ("柳川病院循環"), alight at the "Mihanae" ("御花前") bus stop; a 6‑minute walk.
** Board the {{ill|Horikawa Bus|ja|堀川バス|12=draft}} bound for "Kanpo no Yado Yanagawa" ("かんぽの宿柳川"), alight at the final stop; an 8‑minute walk.
** Approximately 10 minutes by taxi from the station.

