'''Okinohata Suitengu''' (おきのはたすいてんぐう) is a {{ill|Shinto Shrine (Suitengu)|ja|水天宮|lt=Shinto Shrine (Suitengu)|lt_ja=神社（水天宮）|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto Shrine (Suitengu)|qq=}} located in Inarimachi, {{ill|Yanagawa City|ja|柳川市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yanagawa City|qq=}}, {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuoka Prefecture|qq=}}. According to {{ill|Registration|ja|登記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Registration|qq=}}, the registered name of the {{ill|Religious Corporation|ja|宗教法人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Religious Corporation|qq=}} is '''Suitengu''' (すいてんぐう).
== Worshipped deities (Saijin) == {{see also|{{ill|Saijin|ja|祭神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saijin|qq=}}}} * {{ill|Antoku Tennō|ja|安徳天皇|1=Emperor Antoku|2=ja|3=安徳天皇|4=de|5=Antoku|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Antoku Tennō|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Antoku|qq=}}
== Origins == In {{ill|Meiji Era|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji Era|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 2 ({{ill|1869|ja|1869|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1869|qq=}}), a divine fragment ({{ill|Bunrei|ja|分霊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunrei|qq=}}) from the head shrine ({{ill|Main Shrine|ja|本社|lt=Head Shrine|lt_ja=総本社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Main Shrine|qq=}}) of {{ill|Suitengu (Kurume)|ja|水天宮 (久留米市)|lt=Kurume Suitengu|lt_ja=久留米水天宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suitengu (Kurume)|qq=}} was enshrined by means of enshrinement ({{ill|Enshrinement|ja|勧請|lt=Enshrinement|1=Kanjō|2=ja|3=分霊|4=es|5=Bunrei|6=id|7=Kanjō|8=zh|9=分靈|10=fr|11=Kanjō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enshrinement|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanjō|qq=}}); at the same time, the Inari Shrine ({{ill|Inari Shrine|ja|稲荷神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inari Shrine|qq=}}) and Yaken Shrine (弥剣神社 ({{ill|Gion Shrine|ja|祇園社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion Shrine|qq=}})) that existed in the area were combined ({{ill|Combined Enshrinement|ja|合祀|1=co-Enshrinement|2=ja|3=合祀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Combined Enshrinement|13=User:Immanuelle/co-Enshrinement|qq=}}) and established. Note that Inari Shrine was established in {{ill|Bunroku Era|ja|文禄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunroku Era|qq=}} 3 ({{ill|1587|ja|1587|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1587|qq=}}) by {{ill|Tachibana Muneshige|ja|立花宗茂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tachibana Muneshige|qq=}}, while Yaken Shrine was established during the {{ill|Bunka Era|ja|文化 (元号)|lt=Bunka|lt_ja=文化|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunka Era|qq=}} (1804–1818).
Locally, it is called '''Suitengu‑san'''. At the Okinohata Suitengu Festival, held on May 3, 4, and 5, a boat stage known as Sanjinmaru is constructed, and from dusk onwards, Suitengu festival music is performed.
== Festivals == {{ill|File:Fukuoka Yanagawa10s3.jpg|ja|image:Fukuoka Yanagawa10s3.jpg|lt=thumb|extra=Suitengu Grand Festival|extra_ja=水天宮大祭|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/File:Fukuoka Yanagawa10s3.jpg|qq=}} * On the first Horse Day of February: Hatsuuma Festival * May 3–5: Suitengu Grand Festival * July 20–21: Gion Festival
== Access == * Disembark at {{ill|Nishitetsu|ja|西日本鉄道|lt=Nishitetsu|lt_ja=西鉄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishitetsu|qq=}}, {{ill|Nishitetsu Tenjin Omuta Line|ja|西鉄天神大牟田線|lt=Tenjin Omuta Line|lt_ja=天神大牟田線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishitetsu Tenjin Omuta Line|qq=}}, and {{ill|Nishitetsu Yanagawa Station|ja|西鉄柳川駅|lt=Yanagawa Station|lt_ja=柳川駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishitetsu Yanagawa Station|qq=}}; then take the {{ill|Nishitetsu Bus|ja|西鉄バス|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishitetsu Bus|qq=}} bound for “Hayatsue” and alight at the “Suitengu Entrance” bus stop (a 4‑minute walk). * Alternatively, board the same “Hayatsue” bus or the “Yanagawa Hospital Loop” and alight at the “Gohanae” bus stop (a 6‑minute walk). * Or, take the {{ill|Horikawa Bus|ja|堀川バス|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Horikawa Bus|qq=}} bound for “Kanpo no Yado Yanagawa” and alight at its terminal stop (an 8‑minute walk). * Approximately 10 minutes by taxi from the station.
== External Links == {{Commonscat|Okinohata-suitengu}} * [http://sagemon.net/suitengu/ {{ill|Yanagawa City Okinohata Suitengu|ja|柳川市沖端水天宮|lt=Okinohata Suitengu of Yanagawa|lt_ja=沖端水天宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yanagawa City Okinohata Suitengu|qq=}}] (Okinohata Town Youth Division) {{Shinto Side}} {{shinto-stub}}
