'''Okinohata Suitengu''' (おきのはたすいてんぐう) is a [[:en:Suitengū|Shinto Shrine (Suitengu)]] located in Inarimachi, [[:en:Yanagawa, Fukuoka|Yanagawa City]], [[:en:Fukuoka Prefecture|Fukuoka Prefecture]]. According to [[:en:Civil registration|Registration]], the registered name of the {{ill|Religious Corporation|ja|宗教法人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Religious Corporation|qq=}} is '''Suitengu''' (すいてんぐう).
== Worshipped deities (Saijin) == {{see also|{{ill|Saijin|ja|祭神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saijin|qq=}}}} * [[:en:Emperor Antoku|Emperor Antoku]]
== Origins == In [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 2 ({{ill|1869|ja|1869|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1869|qq=}}), a divine fragment ([[:en:Bunrei|Bunrei]]) from the head shrine ([[:en:Corporate headquarters|Head Shrine]]) of [[:en:Kurume Suitengū|Kurume Suitengu]] was enshrined by means of enshrinement ({{ill|Enshrinement|ja|勧請|lt=Enshrinement|1=Kanjō|2=ja|3=分霊|4=es|5=Bunrei|6=id|7=Kanjō|8=zh|9=分靈|10=fr|11=Kanjō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enshrinement|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanjō|qq=}}); at the same time, the Inari Shrine ([[:en:Inari shrine|Inari Shrine]]) and Yaken Shrine (弥剣神社 ({{ill|Gion Shrine|ja|祇園社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion Shrine|qq=}})) that existed in the area were combined ({{ill|Combined Enshrinement|ja|合祀|1=co-Enshrinement|2=ja|3=合祀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Combined Enshrinement|13=User:Immanuelle/co-Enshrinement|qq=}}) and established. Note that Inari Shrine was established in [[:en:Bunroku|Bunroku Era]] 3 ({{ill|1587|ja|1587|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1587|qq=}}) by [[:en:Tachibana Muneshige|Tachibana Muneshige]], while Yaken Shrine was established during the [[:en:Bunka|Bunka]] (1804–1818).
Locally, it is called '''Suitengu‑san'''. At the Okinohata Suitengu Festival, held on May 3, 4, and 5, a boat stage known as Sanjinmaru is constructed, and from dusk onwards, Suitengu festival music is performed.
== Festivals == {{ill|File:Fukuoka Yanagawa10s3.jpg|ja|image:Fukuoka Yanagawa10s3.jpg|lt=thumb|extra=Suitengu Grand Festival|extra_ja=水天宮大祭|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/File:Fukuoka Yanagawa10s3.jpg|qq=}} * On the first Horse Day of February: Hatsuuma Festival * May 3–5: Suitengu Grand Festival * July 20–21: Gion Festival
== Access == * Disembark at [[:en:Nishi-Nippon Railroad|Nishitetsu]], [[:en:Nishitetsu Tenjin Ōmuta Line|Tenjin Omuta Line]], and [[:en:Nishitetsu Yanagawa Station|Yanagawa Station]]; then take the {{ill|Nishitetsu Bus|ja|西鉄バス|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishitetsu Bus|qq=}} bound for “Hayatsue” and alight at the “Suitengu Entrance” bus stop (a 4‑minute walk). * Alternatively, board the same “Hayatsue” bus or the “Yanagawa Hospital Loop” and alight at the “Gohanae” bus stop (a 6‑minute walk). * Or, take the {{ill|Horikawa Bus|ja|堀川バス|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Horikawa Bus|qq=}} bound for “Kanpo no Yado Yanagawa” and alight at its terminal stop (an 8‑minute walk). * Approximately 10 minutes by taxi from the station.
== External Links == {{Commonscat|Okinohata-suitengu}} * [http://sagemon.net/suitengu/ {{ill|Yanagawa City Okinohata Suitengu|ja|柳川市沖端水天宮|lt=Okinohata Suitengu of Yanagawa|lt_ja=沖端水天宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yanagawa City Okinohata Suitengu|qq=}}] (Okinohata Town Youth Division) {{Shinto Side}} {{shinto-stub}}
