== Origins == In [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 2 ([[:en:1869|1869]]), a divine fragment ([[:en:Bunrei|Bunrei]]) from the head shrine ([[:en:Corporate headquarters|Head Shrine]]) of [[:en:Kurume Suitengū|Kurume Suitengu]] was enshrined by means of enshrinement ([[:en:Bunrei|Enshrinement]]); at the same time, the Inari Shrine ([[:en:Inari shrine|Inari Shrine]]) and Yaken Shrine (弥剣神社 ({{ill|Gion Shrine|ja|祇園社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 祇園神社}})) that existed in the area were combined ({{ill|Combined Enshrinement|ja|合祀|1=co-Enshrinement|2=ja|3=合祀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Combined Enshrinement|13=User:Immanuelle/co-Enshrinement|qq=}}) and established. Note that Inari Shrine was established in [[:en:Bunroku|Bunroku Era]] 3 ([[:en:1587|1587]]) by [[:en:Tachibana Muneshige|Tachibana Muneshige]], while Yaken Shrine was established during the [[:en:Bunka|Bunka]] (1804–1818).
Locally, it is called '''Suitengu‑san'''. At the Okinohata Suitengu Festival, held on May 3, 4, and 5, a boat stage known as Sanjinmaru is constructed, and from dusk onwards, Suitengu festival music is performed.
