'''Okinohata Suitengu''' (おきのはたすいてんぐう) is a {{ill|Suitengū|en|Suitengū|WD=Q125319456|lt=Shinto Shrine (Suitengu)|1=Suitengū}} located in Inarimachi, {{ill|Yanagawa, Fukuoka|en|Yanagawa, Fukuoka|WD=Q585630|lt=Yanagawa City|1=Yanagawa, Fukuoka}}, {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|en|Fukuoka Prefecture|WD=Q123258|lt=Fukuoka Prefecture|1=Fukuoka Prefecture}}. According to {{ill|Civil registration|en|Civil registration|WD=Q83708009|lt=Registration|1=Civil registration}}, the registered name of the {{ill|Religious Corporation|ja|宗教法人|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Religious Corporation|1=religious corporation|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q7311343}} is '''Suitengu''' (すいてんぐう).

== Worshipped deities (Saijin) ==
{{see also|{{ill|Saijin|ja|祭神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saijin|qq=}}}}
* {{ill|Emperor Antoku|en|Emperor Antoku|WD=Q316651|lt=Emperor Antoku|1=Emperor Antoku}}

== Origins ==
In {{ill|Meiji era|en|Meiji era|WD=Q3125096|lt=Meiji era|1=Meiji era}} 2 ({{ill|1869|en|1869|WD=Q7720|lt=1869|1=1869}}), a divine fragment ({{ill|Bunrei|en|Bunrei|WD=Q195793|lt=Bunrei|1=Bunrei}}) from the head shrine ({{ill|Corporate headquarters|en|Corporate headquarters|WD=Q1530704|lt=Head Shrine|1=Corporate headquarters}}) of {{ill|Kurume Suitengū|en|Kurume Suitengū|WD=Q3200625|lt=Kurume Suitengu|1=Kurume Suitengū}} was enshrined by means of enshrinement ({{ill|Bunrei|en|Bunrei|WD=Q195793|lt=Enshrinement|1=Bunrei}}); at the same time, the Inari Shrine ({{ill|Inari shrine|en|Inari shrine|WD=Q514480|lt=Inari Shrine|1=Inari shrine}}) and Yaken Shrine (弥剣神社 ({{ill|Gion Shrine|ja|祇園社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion Shrine|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 祇園神社|1=Gion shrines|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11588442}})) that existed in the area were combined ({{ill|Combined Enshrinement|ja|合祀|1=co-Enshrinement|2=ja|3=合祀|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Combined Enshrinement|13=User:Immanuelle/co-Enshrinement|qq=}}) and established. Note that Inari Shrine was established in {{ill|Bunroku|en|Bunroku|WD=Q1373039|lt=Bunroku Era|1=Bunroku}} 3 ({{ill|1587|en|1587|WD=Q6744|lt=1587|1=1587}}) by {{ill|Tachibana Muneshige|en|Tachibana Muneshige|WD=Q1071770|lt=Tachibana Muneshige|1=Tachibana Muneshige}}, while Yaken Shrine was established during the {{ill|Bunka|en|Bunka|WD=Q1373146|lt=Bunka|1=Bunka}} (1804–1818).

Locally, it is called '''Suitengu-san'''. At the Okinohata Suitengu Festival, held on May 3, 4, and 5, a boat stage known as Sanjinmaru is constructed, and from dusk onwards, Suitengu festival music is performed.

== Festivals ==
[[File:Fukuoka Yanagawa10s3.jpg|thumb]]
* On the first Horse Day of February: Hatsuuma Festival
* May 3–5: Suitengu Grand Festival
* July 20–21: Gion Festival

== Access ==
* Disembark at {{ill|Nishi-Nippon Railroad|en|Nishi-Nippon Railroad|WD=Q869251|lt=Nishitetsu|1=Nishi-Nippon Railroad}}, {{ill|Nishitetsu Tenjin Ōmuta Line|en|Nishitetsu Tenjin Ōmuta Line|WD=Q901075|lt=Tenjin Omuta Line|1=Nishitetsu Tenjin Ōmuta Line}}, and {{ill|Nishitetsu Yanagawa Station|en|Nishitetsu Yanagawa Station|WD=Q11629907|lt=Yanagawa Station|1=Nishitetsu Yanagawa Station}}; then take the {{ill|Nishitetsu Bus|ja|西鉄バス|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishitetsu Bus|1=Nishitetsu Bus|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11629843}} bound for “Hayatsue” and alight at the “Suitengu Entrance” bus stop (a 4-minute walk).
* Alternatively, board the same “Hayatsue” bus or the “Yanagawa Hospital Loop” and alight at the “Gohanae” bus stop (a 6-minute walk).
* Or, take the {{ill|Horikawa Bus|ja|堀川バス|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Horikawa Bus|1=Horikawa Bus|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11427415}} bound for “Kanpo no Yado Yanagawa” and alight at its terminal stop (an 8-minute walk).
* Approximately 10 minutes by taxi from the station.

